	<text>
		<body>
			<pb n="1R"/>
				<p><placeName>Tioga Centre</placeName> <date>Sept 16<hi rend="sup">th</hi> 1861</date></p>
				<p><addressee>Rev. I Leeser</addressee></p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Dear Friend&#44;</p>
			<p rend="indent(3)">I presume you did not<lb/> receive a message which I sent you this one<lb/> of my friends in <date>July</date>&#44; informing you of my present address&#44; as both <date>July</date> &#38; <date>August</date>&#44; No.<lb/> of the Occident were directed to <placeName>Binghamton</placeName>&#8212;<lb/> both of which No.&#44; have been forwarded to me.<lb/>  You will please direct here after until you<lb/> hear to the contrary.  To the care of <persName>Mr.<lb/> Gilbert Strang</persName>&#44; <placeName>Tioga Centre&#44; Tioga<lb/> County N Y</placeName>.  I have been here since<lb/> the <date>16th of July</date>&#44; I am again boarding<lb/> in a Christian family&#44; not having heard of<lb/> a Jewish one&#44; to whom I could apply.<lb/>  The family is very small&#44; &#38; I am the only<lb/> Boarder&#44; I should prefer were there two or three<lb/> other pleasant ones&#44; especially as the lady of<lb/> the house is much occupied in her domestic<lb/> duties&#44; her Husband &#38; Son&#44; a lad&#44; compose her<lb/> family.  The place is very small&#44; &#38; quiet&#44; it is 6</p>
			<pb n="1V"/>
				<p>miles from <placeName>Oswego</placeName>.</p>
				<p>I thank you much for supplying my missing<lb/> No of the Occident&#44; some time previous to<lb/> my leaving <placeName>Binghamton</placeName> together with your<lb/> accompanying kind letter.  Soon after the rect.<lb/> of which&#44; in a letter addressed to my cousin<lb/> <persName>Mrs. D. C. Levy</persName>&#44; I asked her to say to you I had<lb/> recd. them &#38; thanked you kindly for the same.<lb/>  I hope she remembered to give you my message.<lb/>  I suppose herself &#38; family have returned to the<lb/> City&#44; if so&#44; when next you see them&#44; please extend<lb/> my love to them.  I regret that you thought<lb/> it hopeless for you to make <add>any</add> effort to become<lb/> the medium of bring<add>ing</add> about <sic>pease</sic> to this dis&#45;<lb/><sic>tructed</sic> Country.  I noticed in some recent papers<lb/> that there are some who are not only opposed to the<lb/> peace&#45;meetings&#44; that have been held in this state<lb/> but denounce them&#44; &#38; since which the press has<lb/> been in some instances silenced &#38; are making every<lb/> effort to urge on this horrible war.  May God in His<lb/> Mercy &#38; wisdom see fit to arrest this cruel war<lb/> at once&#44; &#38; grant us peace &#38; prosperity tho we</p>
			<pb n="2R"/>
				<p>be undeserving some of us.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">With the hope of a brighter future</p>
			<p rend="indent(2)">Truly your friend</p>
			<p rend="indent(3)"><persName role="author">R. A. L.</persName></p>
		</body>
